Method Detail

equals

public final boolean equals(Object obj)
Compares this object with the given object. Two objects are equal if and only if
  1. they belong to the same type equivalence set, and
  2. they have the same "deep structure"
The method determines if these conditions are true by calling #isTypeEquiv and #localEquals on this object, respectively.

This method is invariant with respect to class, and is therefore inherited by all subclasses.

See the paper Implementing Object Equivalence in Java Using the Template Method Design Pattern for more detail about the technique employed here.

Overrides:
equals in class Object
Parameters:
obj - the object with which to compare.
Returns:
true if and only if the objects are type equivalent and equal by "deep comparison".

localEquals

protected boolean localEquals(Object obj)
Compares this object with the given object by doing a "deep comparison" on the two objects. The #equals method (which calls this method) ensures that the two objects are type compatible, therefore the given object may be safely cast to the type of this object for any given implementation of the method.

This implementation always returns true. This permits blind chaining of a hierarchy of localEquals methods.

Subclasses typically override this method. (If the immediate subclass does not override this trivial implementation, then all instances of the subclass are equal by definition.) If a subclass does in fact override this method, it should also override the #getTypeEquiv method. If a subclass does not override this method, instances of the subclass are assumed to have the same "deep structure" as instances of the parent class, that is, the two instances are the same type and therefore belong to the same type equivalence set.

Parameters:
obj - the object with which to compare.
Returns:
true if and only if the objects are equal by "deep comparison".

getTypeEquiv

protected abstract Class getTypeEquiv()
Gets the (non-null) type of this object. More precisely, gets the type of the type equivalence set to which the object belongs.

Immediate subclasses must implement this method. Other subclasses typically override this method. If a subclass does in fact override this method, it should also override the #localEquals method. If a subclass does not override this method, instances of the subclass are assumed to be the same type as instances of the parent class, that is, the two classes belong to the same type equivalence set.

Note that an implementation of this method typically does not return this.getClass(). If it did, a subclass might choose to inherit the method hoping to become type equivalent with its parent class, which would fail.

On the other hand, if an implementation were to return this.getClass() and declare that implementation final, each subclass would be forced into a unique type equivalence set, that is, no two subclasses would be type equivalent.

Returns:
the (non-null) type of this object.
